    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "These will always be zero, until we start supporting deletion. The way deletion is meant to happen is\r\n\r\n- N files can be deleted (no half-deletion of fies). \r\n  - When `N` files are deleted, `M` (where `M >N`) items are deleted. `M` is `itemOffset`. \r\n- The first index-entry is special, it contains `N` and `M`, today always zero.\r\n\r\nHowever, looking into it now, I see that `M` is read from `fileNum`, which is limited to `65K`, being stored as a `uint16`. And `N` (file number) is read from `offset` (4 bytes). \r\n\r\nThis means that we won't handle deletion of more than `65K` items. As far as I can see, this is an error. Since we haven't yet implemented tail-deletion, it should be pretty easy to fix. I need to look into it some more though, to be totally sure that there isn't some other nifty trick going on. ",
